\begin_layout Standard
Human friendly robots in the health care environment are expected to augment
 current human capabilites [minimially invasive surgeries], assist with
 rehabilitation tasks 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jezernik2003,Hesse2000}

\end_inset

, and automate mundane yet critical tasks [perscription filling].
 Specific instances of these systems are already operational [DaVinci, etc]
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jezernik2003}

\end_inset

 and many more exist as prototypes in research labs across the world [research
 examples, unpublished GatorRay paper].
 However, despite the success of these early systems, they typically lack
 any significant level of autonomy.
 To ensure patient and operator safety, these systems are usually just sophistic
ated mechanical extensions of the operator.
 Furthermore, automatic fault or anomoly detection is primarily concerned
 with the hardware anomolys (e.g.
 a corrupt sensor or failed brake circuit).
 More global faults, such as unplanned collisions with a person or the environme
nt are the responsibility of the operator.
 Addressing these and other shortcomings of human-friendly robots is the
 subject current research.
 The aims of this project are focused on developing safe, autonomous motion
 planning algorithms as well as better fault detection algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motion planning problem, has received a lot of attention over the years.
 Its is concerned with finding algorithms which provide robots the ability
 to plan their own movements given a few conditions or constraints by the
 user.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Safer robots means they can be operated in close proximity Operating under
 the assumption that collisions between robot and human are inevatable,
 a community of researchers have sought through mechanical design to make
 such it impossible for a robot to harm a person.
 While proposals have varied, in general these designs share the same set
 of characteristics including, constructed from light weight materials,
 actuated by low maximum torque/velocity actuators, or constructed of flexible
 or compliant links and joints.
 These designs are well conceived, but often the resultant robot becomes
 too weak or inaccurate to perform any real task.
 A second problem is that currently these human-friendly designs are not
 mass produced like their industrial counterparts.
 Therefore, they are more expensive and more difficult to obtain.
\end_layout

