\begin_layout Standard
To fight soaring health care costs and simultaneously increase the quality
 of health care, many researchers are turning to the technologies of robotics
 and intelligent systems to find solutions.
 Over the last decade, there has been an explosion of robotic applications
 in health services ranging from advanced surgery, such as image-guided
 surgery, minimal invasive surgery, and telesurgery, to a variety of home
 healthcare services, including remote health monitoring, telenursing, mobility
 assistance and rehabilitation.
 The Food and Drug Administration, who reviews data on the safety and effectiven
ess of robotic software and hardware, estimates that 36,600 robotic surgeries
 were done in 2005, up nearly 50 percent from 2004.
 Analysts predict the figure will grow at a similar rate in the coming months
 as the general public becomes informed about the advantages of robotically
 assissted surgeries.
 Similarly, robotics technology is becoming more popular in rehabilitation
 and assissted living.
\end_layout

